                            jump to other results
                        </a></div></div><ol class="sense_single" htag="ol"><li class="sense" fkcefr="c1" hclass="sense" id="aupair_sng_1" htag="li"><span class="sensetop" htag="span" hclass="sensetop"><span class="def" htag="span" hclass="def">a young person, usually a woman, who lives with a family in a foreign country in order to learn the language. An <span class="dh">au pair</span> helps in the house and takes care of children and receives a small wage.</span></span><ul class="examples" hclass="examples" htag="ul"><li class="" htag="li"><span class="x">She worked in Paris for six months as an au pair.</span></li><li class="" htag="li"><span class="x">There are very few male au pairs.</span></li><li class="" htag="li"><span class="x">We decided to get an au pair to help with the children.</span></li></ul><span class="topic-g"><span class="prefix">Topics </span><a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/topic/life-stages?level=c1" title="Topic life-stages"><span class="topic" href="l2:people:life_stages?cefr=c1"><span class="topic_name">Life stages</span><span class="topic_cefr">c1</span></span></a><span class="sep">,</span> <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/topic/jobs?level=c1" title="Topic jobs"><span class="topic" href="l2:work_and_business:jobs?cefr=c1"><span class="topic_name">Jobs</span><span class="topic_cefr">c1</span></span></a></span><div class="collapse" htag="div" hclass="collapse"><span class="unbox" unbox="wordorigin" id="aupair_unbox_1"><span class="box_title">Word Origin</span><span class="body"><span class="p">late 19th cent.: from French, literally ‘on equal terms’. The phrase was originally adjectival, describing an arrangement between two parties paid for by the exchange of mutual services; the noun usage dates from the 1960s.</span></span></span></div>    <div id="ring-links-box">
